WEBVTT

00:00:03.632 --> 00:00:08.479
SPEAKER_00: At T-plus 0.678 seconds, the first warning appeared.

00:00:09.181 --> 00:00:13.968
SPEAKER_00: It was smoke from the aft field joint of Challenger's right solid rocket booster.

00:00:14.908 --> 00:00:17.914
SPEAKER_00: More smoke followed through the first two and a half seconds of flight.

00:00:18.795 --> 00:00:19.517
SPEAKER_00: Then it stopped.

00:00:20.477 --> 00:00:23.102
SPEAKER_00: For the next minute, Challenger looked like a launch.

00:00:23.782 --> 00:00:24.744
SPEAKER_00: The vehicle climbed.

00:00:25.386 --> 00:00:26.506
SPEAKER_00: The callouts continued.

00:00:27.128 --> 00:00:30.854
SPEAKER_00: The machinery of the mission appeared to be doing what it had done before.

00:00:30.834 --> 00:00:32.637
SPEAKER_00: but the accident had already begun.

00:00:32.677 --> 00:00:38.527
SPEAKER_00: The visible catastrophe came later, about 73 seconds after liftoff.

00:00:38.546 --> 00:00:40.710
SPEAKER_00: By then the public version could be told quickly.

00:00:40.750 --> 00:00:45.899
SPEAKER_00: It was cold, the O-rings failed, and seven crew members died.

00:00:46.640 --> 00:00:48.403
SPEAKER_00: That version is accurate.

00:00:48.384 --> 00:00:51.649
SPEAKER_00: It is also too small to explain why launch was still allowed.

00:00:52.769 --> 00:00:56.896
SPEAKER_00: The smoke is the better starting point because it separates the consequence from the beginning.

00:00:57.796 --> 00:01:00.180
SPEAKER_00: At 73 seconds, the chain became public.

00:01:00.902 --> 00:01:03.866
SPEAKER_00: At less than one second, the chain became physical.

00:01:04.646 --> 00:01:07.591
SPEAKER_00: Before that, the chain had already been organizational.

00:01:07.570 --> 00:01:09.692
SPEAKER_00: The harder question starts before ignition.

00:01:10.373 --> 00:01:21.025
SPEAKER_00: How does a warning stay visible in records, inspections, memos, charts, and meetings, then arrive at the final decision too weak to stop the machine?

00:01:21.944 --> 00:01:24.787
SPEAKER_00: Challenger did not fail because the danger was invisible.

00:01:25.448 --> 00:01:30.433
SPEAKER_00: It failed after a system learned how to keep flying with evidence that should have made flying harder.

00:01:31.334 --> 00:01:36.379
SPEAKER_00: To understand how that happens, start with the promise the shuttle system had to keep.

00:01:36.360 --> 00:01:39.766
SPEAKER_00: Mercury, Gemini, and Apollo were built around singular missions.

00:01:40.628 --> 00:01:41.771
SPEAKER_00: Dedicated hardware.

00:01:42.451 --> 00:01:43.414
SPEAKER_00: Dedicated risk.

00:01:44.174 --> 00:01:45.658
SPEAKER_00: Dedicated public attention.

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:48.683
SPEAKER_00: The shuttle was designed to break that model.

00:01:49.486 --> 00:01:55.176
SPEAKER_00: Reusable, frequent, routine, less expedition, more airline.

00:01:55.977 --> 00:01:58.503
SPEAKER_00: That promise shaped the organization around it.

00:01:59.191 --> 00:02:03.840
SPEAKER_00: When a program promises routine, every delay starts to mean something different.

00:02:04.703 --> 00:02:21.436
SPEAKER_00: A scrub is still an engineering decision, but it is also a schedule problem, a budget problem, a public problem, a problem that moves through contracts, payload windows, congressional expectations, and the reputation of the agency.

00:02:21.415 --> 00:02:29.242
SPEAKER_00: NASA entered 1986 with an aggressive flight schedule and a system that had to justify itself through repetition.

00:02:30.163 --> 00:02:33.967
SPEAKER_00: The shuttle was not only a spacecraft, it was an operating model.

00:02:34.828 --> 00:02:40.933
SPEAKER_00: The first thing to understand about Challenger is that the program was built to make spaceflight feel normal.

00:02:41.894 --> 00:02:43.536
SPEAKER_00: Normal operation is useful.

00:02:44.276 --> 00:02:50.241
SPEAKER_00: It is also dangerous when it teaches people to treat unresolved problems as background conditions.

00:02:50.693 --> 00:02:53.860
SPEAKER_00: No one in this story needed to wake up wanting a disaster.

00:02:53.920 --> 00:02:58.631
SPEAKER_00: That matters because the easy version turns the accident into a morality play.

00:02:59.491 --> 00:03:03.020
SPEAKER_00: Bad people made bad choices, so better people would have stopped it.

00:03:03.942 --> 00:03:05.985
SPEAKER_00: The record is harder than that.

00:03:06.270 --> 00:03:12.997
SPEAKER_00: The system was full of people trying to do their jobs inside a decision structure that kept lowering the force of warnings.

00:03:13.859 --> 00:03:15.982
SPEAKER_00: Three pressures were running at the same time.

00:03:16.902 --> 00:03:19.126
SPEAKER_00: First, technical uncertainty.

00:03:19.865 --> 00:03:22.008
SPEAKER_00: The shuttle was enormously complex.

00:03:22.710 --> 00:03:30.218
SPEAKER_00: Each flight produced new evidence about how hardware behaved in the real vehicle, under real loads, in real weather.

00:03:30.199 --> 00:03:34.723
SPEAKER_00: That gap between design expectation and operating evidence is normal in engineering.

00:03:35.425 --> 00:03:37.546
SPEAKER_00: What matters is how the gap gets handled.

00:03:38.608 --> 00:03:40.870
SPEAKER_00: Second, schedule pressure.

00:03:41.610 --> 00:03:44.114
SPEAKER_00: Delays did not move one item on one calendar.

00:03:44.713 --> 00:03:49.740
SPEAKER_00: They shifted payloads, crews, customers, reviews, and promises.

00:03:50.580 --> 00:03:53.082
SPEAKER_00: The cost of stopping was visible immediately.

00:03:54.204 --> 00:03:57.707
SPEAKER_00: Third, institutional reputation.

00:03:57.687 --> 00:04:00.171
SPEAKER_00: NASA was not only an engineering organization.

00:04:00.893 --> 00:04:06.381
SPEAKER_00: It was a national symbol, a funding case, a Cold War instrument, and a public trust.

00:04:07.201 --> 00:04:09.746
SPEAKER_00: These pressures met inside the same rooms.

00:04:10.467 --> 00:04:14.853
SPEAKER_00: When they conflicted, the most flexible thing was often uncertainty.

00:04:14.832 --> 00:04:16.995
SPEAKER_00: A technical concern could be reframed.

00:04:17.675 --> 00:04:18.637
SPEAKER_00: It could be qualified.

00:04:19.337 --> 00:04:21.019
SPEAKER_00: It could be moved to the next review.

00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:24.023
SPEAKER_00: Schedule and reputation were harder to bend.

00:04:24.882 --> 00:04:26.644
SPEAKER_00: So the practical standard drifted.

00:04:26.665 --> 00:04:32.630
SPEAKER_00: The question became, keep flying unless the evidence against flying is overwhelming.

00:04:33.432 --> 00:04:39.017
SPEAKER_00: That is very different from, do not fly unless the evidence for safety is clear.

00:04:38.997 --> 00:04:41.622
SPEAKER_00: The difference showed up most clearly in one component.

00:04:42.504 --> 00:04:47.916
SPEAKER_00: The shuttle used two solid rocket boosters for most of its thrust during the first two minutes of flight.

00:04:48.858 --> 00:04:52.365
SPEAKER_00: Each booster was not built as one continuous piece.

00:04:52.386 --> 00:04:57.817
SPEAKER_00: It was assembled from cylindrical segments, stacked and joined at the launch site.

00:04:57.797 --> 00:05:00.540
SPEAKER_00: Where the segments met, there was a field joint.

00:05:01.321 --> 00:05:11.291
SPEAKER_00: Inside that joint, two rubber O-rings, a primary and a secondary, were supposed to seal the gap and keep hot combustion gases inside the booster.

00:05:12.153 --> 00:05:13.675
SPEAKER_00: The joint had to seal quickly.

00:05:14.375 --> 00:05:17.560
SPEAKER_00: Pressure inside the motor could distort the metal parts at ignition.

00:05:18.341 --> 00:05:23.146
SPEAKER_00: The O-rings had to move into position fast enough to block hot gas before it escaped.

00:05:23.632 --> 00:05:26.735
SPEAKER_00: Cold mattered because rubber does not respond the same way in cold.

00:05:27.637 --> 00:05:31.379
SPEAKER_00: A seal that moves quickly when warm can respond more slowly when cold.

00:05:32.141 --> 00:05:35.124
SPEAKER_00: In this joint, timing was not a detail.

00:05:35.925 --> 00:05:38.026
SPEAKER_00: Timing was the safety margin.

00:05:38.846 --> 00:05:42.209
SPEAKER_00: If the seals failed, there was no graceful backup.

00:05:42.891 --> 00:05:50.298
SPEAKER_00: Hot gas could burn through the booster casing, reach surrounding structure, and turn a local leak into a vehicle failure.

00:05:50.665 --> 00:05:53.550
SPEAKER_00: The O-ring problem had been showing itself before Challenger.

00:05:54.511 --> 00:05:57.454
SPEAKER_00: Post-flight inspections found erosion on the primary seal.

00:05:58.235 --> 00:06:02.422
SPEAKER_00: In some cases, gas had blown past it and left evidence deeper in the joint.

00:06:03.423 --> 00:06:05.024
SPEAKER_00: Engineers documented the damage.

00:06:05.646 --> 00:06:06.266
SPEAKER_00: They measured it.

00:06:06.908 --> 00:06:07.668
SPEAKER_00: They reported it.

00:06:08.470 --> 00:06:10.952
SPEAKER_00: The dangerous part is what happened next.

00:06:11.303 --> 00:06:20.589
SPEAKER_00: Because the mission succeeded, because the vehicles came home, damage could be processed as evidence that the system had tolerated the condition.

00:06:21.632 --> 00:06:24.880
SPEAKER_00: A damaged component in a surviving system can be read two ways.

00:06:25.863 --> 00:06:27.288
SPEAKER_00: One reading says,

00:06:27.267 --> 00:06:32.856
SPEAKER_00: We were closer to failure than we should have been, so we stop and fix the condition before we repeat it.

00:06:33.658 --> 00:06:41.610
SPEAKER_00: The other says, the vehicle survived, the margin held, and the risk can be carried while improvement work continues.

00:06:42.613 --> 00:06:45.978
SPEAKER_00: The second reading became easier each time the shuttle flew and returned.

00:06:46.658 --> 00:06:52.127
SPEAKER_00: What had started as a serious anomaly gradually became part of the operating history.

00:06:52.108 --> 00:06:54.089
SPEAKER_00: The O-ring warning did not disappear.

00:06:54.910 --> 00:06:55.370
SPEAKER_00: It moved.

00:06:56.172 --> 00:06:59.113
SPEAKER_00: That is how a warning can die inside a large organization.

00:07:00.014 --> 00:07:01.696
SPEAKER_00: Not through silence.

00:07:01.716 --> 00:07:02.697
SPEAKER_00: Through translation.

00:07:03.738 --> 00:07:06.319
SPEAKER_00: It starts when an engineer sees something wrong.

00:07:07.060 --> 00:07:08.461
SPEAKER_00: The data is specific.

00:07:09.043 --> 00:07:10.363
SPEAKER_00: The language is uncomfortable.

00:07:10.983 --> 00:07:11.444
SPEAKER_00: Erosion.

00:07:12.024 --> 00:07:12.485
SPEAKER_00: Blow-by.

00:07:13.146 --> 00:07:13.747
SPEAKER_00: Heat effects.

00:07:14.466 --> 00:07:17.290
SPEAKER_00: A seal that did not behave the way the design assumed.

00:07:18.271 --> 00:07:20.833
SPEAKER_00: Precise evidence has force.

00:07:20.812 --> 00:07:23.076
SPEAKER_00: then the evidence becomes a discussion item.

00:07:23.778 --> 00:07:30.648
SPEAKER_00: It enters a meeting with dozens of other concerns, other anomalies, other systems, other deadlines.

00:07:31.449 --> 00:07:34.754
SPEAKER_00: The context broadens and the urgency flattens.

00:07:35.394 --> 00:07:38.279
SPEAKER_00: From there, the discussion becomes a judgment call.

00:07:39.021 --> 00:07:41.184
SPEAKER_00: Does this affect the next flight?

00:07:41.163 --> 00:07:44.288
SPEAKER_00: The answer depends on the question the room decides to ask.

00:07:45.071 --> 00:07:48.255
SPEAKER_00: If the question is, can we prove this will cause a failure?

00:07:48.896 --> 00:07:50.118
SPEAKER_00: The answer is usually no.

00:07:50.980 --> 00:07:54.026
SPEAKER_00: Predicting a specific loss on a specific flight is hard.

00:07:54.807 --> 00:07:57.791
SPEAKER_00: If the question is, can we prove this will not fail?

00:07:58.353 --> 00:07:59.574
SPEAKER_00: The answer is also no.

00:08:00.355 --> 00:08:02.620
SPEAKER_00: But the first question keeps the schedule alive.

00:08:03.562 --> 00:08:06.226
SPEAKER_00: Then the judgment becomes a schedule decision.

00:08:06.206 --> 00:08:07.747
SPEAKER_00: The language changes again.

00:08:07.767 --> 00:08:11.971
SPEAKER_00: It is no longer mainly about erosion depth or ceiling time.

00:08:12.752 --> 00:08:15.115
SPEAKER_00: It is about whether there is enough cause to delay.

00:08:16.117 --> 00:08:17.358
SPEAKER_00: Delay has a phone tree.

00:08:18.038 --> 00:08:19.019
SPEAKER_00: Delay has cost.

00:08:19.740 --> 00:08:21.081
SPEAKER_00: Delay has a visible owner.

00:08:22.083 --> 00:08:25.606
SPEAKER_00: If the flight succeeds, the decision becomes precedent.

00:08:26.387 --> 00:08:28.310
SPEAKER_00: We flew with that condition and came back.

00:08:29.271 --> 00:08:32.413
SPEAKER_00: That fact starts to compete with the warning that preceded it.

00:08:33.175 --> 00:08:36.077
SPEAKER_00: This route ran more than once before Challenger.

00:08:36.057 --> 00:08:38.720
SPEAKER_00: Each pass made the next one easier to defend.

00:08:39.520 --> 00:08:47.668
SPEAKER_00: Engineers were not simply ignored, they were often heard, then absorbed into a process that had learned how to carry their concern without stopping.

00:08:48.609 --> 00:08:57.817
SPEAKER_00: Months before Challenger, Roger Boisjolie warned that a similar field-joint problem could lead to catastrophe of the highest order and loss of human life.

00:08:58.918 --> 00:09:01.081
SPEAKER_00: That memo did not come from hindsight.

00:09:01.921 --> 00:09:06.065
SPEAKER_00: It came from inside the system, before the accident,

00:09:06.044 --> 00:09:08.187
SPEAKER_00: from an engineer close to the hardware.

00:09:09.109 --> 00:09:13.014
SPEAKER_00: The temperature pattern also had more weight than the launch night argument made it feel.

00:09:13.816 --> 00:09:19.023
SPEAKER_00: When the full flight history was framed one way, the cold weather signal could look debatable.

00:09:20.085 --> 00:09:26.734
SPEAKER_00: When the full record was framed another way, cold O-ring distress became much harder to dismiss.

00:09:27.615 --> 00:09:34.043
SPEAKER_00: A chart can contain real information and still weaken the warning if it frames the wrong question.

00:09:34.243 --> 00:09:37.770
SPEAKER_00: Richard Feynman's later appendix named the broader danger plainly.

00:09:38.533 --> 00:09:41.119
SPEAKER_00: Previous success can become misleading evidence.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.385
SPEAKER_00: A survived flight can show that the vehicle got through.

00:09:44.426 --> 00:09:47.513
SPEAKER_00: It does not prove the risk was safe to repeat.

00:09:48.775 --> 00:09:53.466
SPEAKER_00: By January 1986, Challenger was not facing a new problem.

00:09:53.548 --> 00:09:55.691
SPEAKER_00: The program had evidence of O-ring distress.

00:09:56.390 --> 00:09:57.592
SPEAKER_00: It had temperature concern.

00:09:58.234 --> 00:09:58.975
SPEAKER_00: It had waivers.

00:09:59.534 --> 00:10:00.275
SPEAKER_00: It had memos.

00:10:00.856 --> 00:10:02.719
SPEAKER_00: It had a known field-joint problem.

00:10:03.379 --> 00:10:07.966
SPEAKER_00: It had a launch system that kept treating survival as part of the safety case.

00:10:07.985 --> 00:10:10.889
SPEAKER_00: Then the weather turned that old problem into a launch decision.

00:10:11.769 --> 00:10:14.533
SPEAKER_00: January 27th, 1986.

00:10:15.595 --> 00:10:18.778
SPEAKER_00: Less than 24 hours before the scheduled launch.

00:10:18.759 --> 00:10:28.654
SPEAKER_00: A teleconference connected NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center, Kennedy Space Center, and Morton Thiokol, the contractor that built the solid rocket boosters.

00:10:29.576 --> 00:10:31.679
SPEAKER_00: The subject was temperature.

00:10:32.640 --> 00:10:38.910
SPEAKER_00: Forecasts and engineering estimates pointed to launch conditions far colder than prior shuttle experience.

00:10:38.890 --> 00:10:42.216
SPEAKER_00: The launch temperature would be about 36 degrees Fahrenheit.

00:10:43.158 --> 00:10:50.008
SPEAKER_00: The right aft field joint was estimated colder, around 28 degrees Fahrenheit, plus or minus 5 degrees.

00:10:50.889 --> 00:10:57.119
SPEAKER_00: Theocole engineers were concerned because cold could slow the O-rings at the exact moment they needed to seal.

00:10:57.504 --> 00:10:58.986
SPEAKER_00: Their recommendation was clear.

00:10:59.047 --> 00:11:03.015
SPEAKER_00: Do not launch below 53 degrees Fahrenheit.

00:11:03.736 --> 00:11:09.629
SPEAKER_00: That number mattered because it was tied to the lowest relevant prior experience they believed they could defend.

00:11:10.731 --> 00:11:12.215
SPEAKER_00: NASA managers pushed back.

00:11:12.937 --> 00:11:16.423
SPEAKER_00: In a technical review, pushback can be necessary.

00:11:16.707 --> 00:11:19.352
SPEAKER_00: The danger was the standard that began to govern the room.

00:11:20.274 --> 00:11:21.275
SPEAKER_00: The question drifted.

00:11:22.278 --> 00:11:24.081
SPEAKER_00: Show that this is safe to fly.

00:11:24.782 --> 00:11:26.765
SPEAKER_00: Became prove that it will fail.

00:11:26.826 --> 00:11:29.851
SPEAKER_00: That shift reversed the burden of proof.

00:11:30.832 --> 00:11:36.984
SPEAKER_00: Instead of requiring evidence that launch was safe, the process demanded evidence that failure was certain.

00:11:37.985 --> 00:11:41.230
SPEAKER_00: Engineering evidence usually does not arrive that way.

00:11:41.211 --> 00:11:50.611
SPEAKER_00: It arrives as a missing margin, a condition outside experience, a trend with enough signal to matter before the catastrophe supplies certainty.

00:11:50.652 --> 00:11:53.798
SPEAKER_00: The engineers had evidence of risk.

00:11:53.818 --> 00:11:57.687
SPEAKER_00: They did not have an equation that converted temperature into guaranteed loss of vehicle.

00:11:58.328 --> 00:12:01.294
SPEAKER_00: That absence became useful to the launch case.

00:12:01.274 --> 00:12:03.538
SPEAKER_00: Theocole asked for an offline caucus.

00:12:04.278 --> 00:12:07.663
SPEAKER_00: The caucus lasted far longer than the five minutes first requested.

00:12:08.384 --> 00:12:11.067
SPEAKER_00: When they returned, the recommendation had changed.

00:12:11.807 --> 00:12:15.312
SPEAKER_00: The new position was that the data was inconclusive and launch could proceed.

00:12:15.331 --> 00:12:17.475
SPEAKER_00: The cold had not changed.

00:12:18.034 --> 00:12:19.756
SPEAKER_00: The joint had not changed.

00:12:20.398 --> 00:12:22.200
SPEAKER_00: The limits of the data had not changed.

00:12:22.860 --> 00:12:24.283
SPEAKER_00: The decision frame changed.

00:12:25.183 --> 00:12:29.408
SPEAKER_00: One instruction from that caucus still carries the shape of the moment.

00:12:29.811 --> 00:12:34.826
SPEAKER_00: Jerry Mason told Bob Lund to take off his engineering hat and put on his management hat.

00:12:35.649 --> 00:12:37.636
SPEAKER_00: No single phrase explains the disaster.

00:12:37.697 --> 00:12:40.546
SPEAKER_00: No single person explains it either.

00:12:41.066 --> 00:12:49.817
SPEAKER_00: The deeper fact is that the same process could take a specific engineering objection and return a launch recommendation from the same evidence.

00:12:50.499 --> 00:12:54.424
SPEAKER_00: The launch eve reversal is dramatic, but it is not the whole failure.

00:12:55.186 --> 00:12:57.849
SPEAKER_00: A warning also has to travel.

00:12:58.570 --> 00:13:10.567
SPEAKER_00: It has to move from hardware to engineers, from engineers to managers, from contractors to NASA, from lower review levels to the people with authority to stop the launch.

00:13:10.547 --> 00:13:13.149
SPEAKER_00: At each step, the signal can be compressed.

00:13:14.009 --> 00:13:24.339
SPEAKER_00: Compression is normal in large programs, but when compression changes an active objection into a resolved item, the system has made a decision without naming it directly.

00:13:25.139 --> 00:13:26.741
SPEAKER_00: Safety should have been a backstop.

00:13:27.461 --> 00:13:40.553
SPEAKER_00: The Commission later criticized weak problem reporting, inadequate trend analysis, misrepresented criticality, and safety structures that did not give the concern enough independent force at the decisive points.

00:13:40.533 --> 00:13:50.644
SPEAKER_00: People can care about safety while the way decisions are made still lets a warning arrive too late, too thin, or too resolved to change action.

00:13:51.726 --> 00:14:04.198
SPEAKER_00: By launch morning, the warning had passed through hardware evidence, paperwork, meetings, waivers, charts, recommendation, caucus, and management acceptance.

00:14:04.219 --> 00:14:07.402
SPEAKER_00: At the end of that route, launch was still open.

00:14:07.702 --> 00:14:09.870
SPEAKER_00: At 1138 A.M.

00:14:10.732 --> 00:14:18.235
SPEAKER_00: Eastern Standard Time on January 28, 1986, Challenger launched from Kennedy Space Center.

00:14:18.890 --> 00:14:23.176
SPEAKER_00: Within the first second, smoke appeared near the right aft field joint.

00:14:23.895 --> 00:14:26.919
SPEAKER_00: The primary O-ring had not sealed the way it needed to seal.

00:14:27.721 --> 00:14:33.326
SPEAKER_00: The secondary O-ring, affected by cold and joint movement, had not saved the joint in time.

00:14:34.187 --> 00:14:37.451
SPEAKER_00: The smoke continued through roughly T plus two and a half seconds.

00:14:38.231 --> 00:14:39.092
SPEAKER_00: Then it disappeared.

00:14:39.933 --> 00:14:44.678
SPEAKER_00: The commission considered that combustion residue may have temporarily sealed the breach.

00:14:44.827 --> 00:14:49.693
SPEAKER_00: For a short time, the vehicle could look normal while the failure chain remained alive.

00:14:50.595 --> 00:14:54.720
SPEAKER_00: That temporary quiet is one of the clearest details in the record.

00:14:55.701 --> 00:14:59.085
SPEAKER_00: The physical system did what the organization had been doing for years.

00:14:59.926 --> 00:15:05.552
SPEAKER_00: A sign of breach appeared, an explanation arrived, and flight continued.

00:15:05.533 --> 00:15:10.279
SPEAKER_00: Around 58 to 59 seconds into flight, flame became visible again.

00:15:10.299 --> 00:15:16.950
SPEAKER_00: Hot gas from the right booster began damaging surrounding structure, including the external tank area.

00:15:17.910 --> 00:15:21.517
SPEAKER_00: At approximately 73 seconds, Challenger broke apart.

00:15:22.477 --> 00:15:34.696
SPEAKER_00: Francis Dick Scobie, Michael Smith, Judith Resnick, Ellison Onizuka, Ronald McNair, Gregory Jarvis, and Krista McAuliffe were lost.

00:15:34.811 --> 00:15:36.933
SPEAKER_00: The visible failure lasted seconds.

00:15:37.716 --> 00:15:40.179
SPEAKER_00: The invisible one had been accumulating for years.

00:15:41.101 --> 00:15:44.386
SPEAKER_00: What came next was the question every institution fears.

00:15:45.148 --> 00:15:47.692
SPEAKER_00: How did this happen when the evidence already existed?

00:15:48.653 --> 00:15:52.941
SPEAKER_00: President Reagan appointed the Rogers Commission, chaired by William Rogers.

00:15:53.981 --> 00:16:00.633
SPEAKER_00: Richard Feynman was one of its members, and his independent work became part of the public memory of the investigation.

00:16:01.119 --> 00:16:02.782
SPEAKER_00: The physical cause was direct.

00:16:03.504 --> 00:16:12.582
SPEAKER_00: Failure of the seal in the right booster's aft field joint, hot gas escaping, damage to the external tank area, and vehicle breakup.

00:16:13.465 --> 00:16:16.630
SPEAKER_00: The Commission did not stop at the physical cause.

00:16:16.610 --> 00:16:19.434
SPEAKER_00: It found a flawed launch decision process.

00:16:20.196 --> 00:16:21.658
SPEAKER_00: It found communication failures.

00:16:22.438 --> 00:16:34.096
SPEAKER_00: It found that crucial information about O-ring history, temperature concern, and continuing engineering opposition did not reach key decision makers with the force and clarity it needed.

00:16:34.115 --> 00:16:39.683
SPEAKER_00: The people closest to the hardware had the sharpest version of the risk.

00:16:39.703 --> 00:16:44.490
SPEAKER_00: The people with the authority to stop launch received a softened version of it.

00:16:44.471 --> 00:16:52.719
SPEAKER_00: The Commission described the immediate failure, the part, the launch decision, and the communication system that softened the warning.

00:16:53.679 --> 00:16:58.465
SPEAKER_00: Diane Vaughan later named the larger pattern, the normalization of deviance.

00:16:59.426 --> 00:17:04.169
SPEAKER_00: A deviation from expected performance becomes normal because the system keeps surviving it.

00:17:05.091 --> 00:17:08.395
SPEAKER_00: The phrase is useful because it does not require a conspiracy.

00:17:09.294 --> 00:17:12.958
SPEAKER_00: It describes a slow adjustment in what feels acceptable.

00:17:13.328 --> 00:17:17.559
SPEAKER_00: The line moves because each previous crossing did not end in catastrophe.

00:17:18.542 --> 00:17:27.825
SPEAKER_00: Challenger is taught in engineering programs, business schools, and organizational behavior courses because the pattern is not limited to NASA.

00:17:28.059 --> 00:17:31.683
SPEAKER_00: Repeated near misses create false confidence.

00:17:31.703 --> 00:17:36.829
SPEAKER_00: Every time a system survives a close call, perceived risk can drop.

00:17:37.570 --> 00:17:40.733
SPEAKER_00: The near miss gets counted as validation instead of warning.

00:17:41.494 --> 00:17:43.555
SPEAKER_00: Missing data gets mistaken for safety.

00:17:44.437 --> 00:17:52.166
SPEAKER_00: No evidence of failure is not the same as evidence of no failure, especially when the dangerous condition has not really been tested.

00:17:53.246 --> 00:17:56.851
SPEAKER_00: Schedule pressure changes prove standards quietly.

00:17:56.831 --> 00:17:59.156
SPEAKER_00: No one has to announce that the bar has moved.

00:17:59.816 --> 00:18:05.850
SPEAKER_00: The bar for stopping can rise inch by inch until only certainty of disaster justifies delay.

00:18:06.973 --> 00:18:09.879
SPEAKER_00: Institutions reward continuity over interruption.

00:18:10.838 --> 00:18:17.631
SPEAKER_00: The person who keeps the line moving is easier to celebrate than the person who stops it for a risk that might never become visible.

00:18:18.633 --> 00:18:20.358
SPEAKER_00: Anomalies become background noise.

00:18:21.139 --> 00:18:24.325
SPEAKER_00: The first time something unexpected happens, it gets attention.

00:18:25.388 --> 00:18:27.472
SPEAKER_00: The fifth time, a tracking number.

00:18:28.494 --> 00:18:29.335
SPEAKER_00: The tenth time,

00:18:29.939 --> 00:18:32.205
SPEAKER_00: It starts to sound like how the system works.

00:18:33.227 --> 00:18:39.802
SPEAKER_00: These behaviors appear wherever the cost of stopping is immediate, and the cost of continuing is statistical.

00:18:40.624 --> 00:18:46.918
SPEAKER_00: Health care systems, financial systems, infrastructure, software.

00:18:46.899 --> 00:18:52.308
SPEAKER_00: Any organization that has to decide whether a warning is strong enough to interrupt momentum.

00:18:53.290 --> 00:18:55.152
SPEAKER_00: Challenger did not invent this pattern.

00:18:55.914 --> 00:18:57.116
SPEAKER_00: It made the pattern visible.

00:18:58.017 --> 00:19:00.522
SPEAKER_00: Disasters rarely begin at the moment of impact.

00:19:01.263 --> 00:19:07.793
SPEAKER_00: They begin when a system gets used to explaining away what it should have stopped to understand.

00:19:07.774 --> 00:19:13.420
SPEAKER_00: Challenger was a long sequence of accommodations, each one easier to defend than the whole chain would have been.

00:19:14.421 --> 00:19:19.748
SPEAKER_00: The smoke at T plus 0.678 seconds is why the story should not start with the explosion.

00:19:20.689 --> 00:19:24.293
SPEAKER_00: The first visible warning was small, then it vanished.

00:19:25.176 --> 00:19:27.958
SPEAKER_00: For a while, everything looked normal.

00:19:27.938 --> 00:19:30.526
SPEAKER_00: The same thing had already happened inside the organization.

00:19:31.448 --> 00:19:32.231
SPEAKER_00: A warning appeared.

00:19:33.053 --> 00:19:34.137
SPEAKER_00: The system explained it.

00:19:34.819 --> 00:19:35.722
SPEAKER_00: The launch continued.

00:19:36.444 --> 00:19:38.530
SPEAKER_00: Next time, another design failure.

00:19:39.171 --> 00:19:42.420
SPEAKER_00: Another system that taught itself to ignore what it already knew.

